date=March 30, 2020 |location=United States |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of previous Days of Our Lives cast members|List of previous ''Days of Our Lives'' cast members]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Days of Our Lives}}\n{{Days of Our Lives characters}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Days of Our Lives cast members, List of}}\n[[Category:Lists of actors by soap opera television series|Days of our Lives]]\n[[Category:Days of Our Lives]]\n", "name_user": "JJonathan1989", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eDebuting)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Days_of_Our_Lives_cast_members"}
{"title_page": "John Taylor (mining engineer)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n[[File:John Taylor (civil engineer).jpg|thumb|250px|John Taylor]]\n'''John Taylor''' (22 August 1779, in [[Norwich]] \u2013 5 April 1863, in London) was a British [[mining engineer]].<ref name=DNB/>\n\n==Life==\nTaylor was the son of [[John Taylor (Unitarian hymn writer)|John]] and [[Susannah Taylor]]. He was the brother of [[Philip Taylor (civil engineer)|Philip Taylor]].<ref name=DNB>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Taylor, Philip}}</ref>\n\n===Business interests===\nMany of Taylor\u2019s business interests were backed by the [[Martineau family]]. In 1796 he improvised a mechanised copper ore crusher at [[Wheal Friendship]], a mine just outside [[Tavistock, Devon]]. This machine was improved over time and became widely adopted; it was known as the \"Cornish rolls\".<ref>{{Cite book\n|last=Earl\n|first=Bryan\n|title=Cornish Mining: The Techniques of Metal Mining in the West of England, Past and Present\n|publisher=Cornish Hillside Publications\n|location=St Austell\n|edition=2nd\n|year=1994\n|page=80\n|isbn=978-0-9519419-3-5}}</ref> Two years later, in 1798, when he was only 19 years old, he became the manager of this mine.<ref name=DNB/><ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/insideout/southwest/series9/week_five.shtml\n|title=BBC Inside Out \u2013 Tavistock Canal\n|publisher=BBC\n|accessdate=10 August 2009}}</ref> Taylor\u2019s sons and [[Peter Finch Martineau]]\u2019s son and grandson were still active in its operations and oversight nearly a century later.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ronalds|first=B.F.|date=February 2018|title=Peter Finch Martineau and his Son|url=|journal=The Martineau Society Newsletter|volume=41|pages=10\u201319|via=}}</ref> \n\nFrom 1803 to 1817 Taylor oversaw the construction of the [[Tavistock Canal]], which linked the town of Tavistock to [[Morwellham Quay]] on the [[River Tamar]], where cargo was loaded into ships.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.towpathtreks.co.uk/Other/tavistock_canal.html\n|title=Towpath Treks: The Tavistock Canal and Morwellham Quay\n|publisher=towpathtreks.co.uk\n|accessdate=10 August 2009}}</ref><ref name=CORN>\n{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.cornish-mining.org.uk/pdf/Cornwall_west_devon_Mining_Landscape_WHS_Nomination_Document_Parts3b_c_d_e.pdf\n |title       = The Cornwall and West Devon Mining Landscape Description of Property, 3b\n |publisher   = Cornwall Council\n |accessdate  = 10 August 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071004233515/http://www.cornish-mining.org.uk/pdf/Cornwall_west_devon_Mining_Landscape_WHS_Nomination_Document_Parts3b_c_d_e.pdf\n |archivedate = 4 October 2007\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1812 Taylor set up as a chemical manufacturer at [[Stratford, Essex]].<ref name=DNB/> This enterprise, also funded by the Martineaus, set out to produce [[vitriol]], but as Taylor & Martineau became widely diversified.<ref name=\"ODNB\">{{cite ODNB|id=27059|title=Taylor, John|first=Edmund|last=Newell}}</ref> One of Taylor's interests was sugar refining, for which he took out a patent in 1815 for a pressure method for separation of sugar from [[molasses]]. The use of heated animal oils in sugar processes disclosed the production of [[naphtha]].<ref>[[June Z. Fullmer]], ''Technology, Chemistry, and the Law in Early 19th-Century England'', Technology and Culture Vol. 21, No. 1 (Jan. 1980), pp. 1\u201328, at p. 8 and p. 16. Published by: The Johns Hopkins University Press on behalf of the Society for the History of Technology. Stable URL: https://www.jstor.org/stable/3103985</ref> Taylor took out another patent in 1815, for decomposing animal oils into gas.<ref>{{cite book|author=William Matthews|title=An historical sketch of the origin and progress of gas-lighting|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PZpLAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA95|accessdate=12 April 2013|year=1832|publisher=Simpkin & Marshall|page=95}}</ref> This discovery led Taylor & Martineau into 1823 to what Philip Taylor's son later wrote of as \"the battle of the gases\": the commercial contest between [[gas lighting]] derived from coal and from oils.<ref>Philip Meadows Taylor, ''A Memoir of the family of Taylor of Norwich'' (1886), p. 52;[http://wayward.archive.org/stream/memoiroffamilyof00tayl#page/n111/mode/2up archive.org.]</ref> John Taylor's direction in the 1820s, however, was back into mining.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n\nIn 1819 Taylor raised the \u00a365,000 needed to re-open the [[Consolidated Mines]] in [[Gwennap]], Cornwall. This mine employed over 3,000 people and became the most productive in Cornwall, yielding almost 450,000 tons of copper ore.<ref>{{Cite book\n|last=Barton\n|first=D. B.\n|title=A History of Copper Mining in Cornwall and Devon\n|publisher=D. Bradford Barton Ltd\n|location=Truro\n|year=1978\n|edition=3rd\n|pages=51, 95\n|isbn=}}</ref> He was also mineral agent to the [[Duke of Devonshire]] and to the commissioners of [[Greenwich Hospital (London)|Greenwich Hospital]].<ref name=DNB/>\n\nIn 1824 he built the [[Redruth and Chasewater Railway]] to transport the ore from Consolidated Mines and others nearby to the port at [[Devoran]].<ref name=CORN/>\n\nIn 1824 he also began a major expansion of the copper mines at [[Coniston, Cumbria|Coniston]] in [[Cumbria]], making them \"the largest and most profitable copper mines in the north\".<ref name=\"Cumbria-industries-copper-mining\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cumbria-industries.org.uk/a-z-of-industries/copper/ |title=Copper |last=Fleming |first=P. |date=2014 |website=Industrial History of Cumbria |access-date=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1836 he erected a new engine at [[Penrhyn D\u00fb Mines|Penrhyn Du]] and held a lease from 1838<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bennett|first=John|title=Metal Mines Of Llanengan|last2=Vernon|first2=Robert|publisher=Gwydyr Mines Publications|year=|isbn=0951479881|location=Cheshire|pages=40}}</ref>\n\n===Intellectual life===\nIn 1807 Taylor was elected a Fellow of the [[Geological Society]], and acted as treasurer from 1816 to 1844. In 1825 he was elected a Fellow of the [[Royal Society]], and was one of the founders of the [[British Association]] on 26 June 1832, holding the office of treasurer till September 1861. He was one of the founders of [[University College, London]], to which he acted as treasurer for many years.<ref name=DNB/>\n\n==Works==\nTaylor was the author of ''Statements concerning the Profits of Mining in England'' (London, 1825), edited ''Records of Mining'' in 1829, and contributed articles to scientific journals.<ref name=DNB/> A list of his publications may be found in the appendix of R. Burt, ''John Taylor, mining entrepreneur and engineer, 1779\u20131863'', Moorland Publishing Company, 1977. He contributed articles on mining to ''[[Rees's Cyclop\u00e6dia]]''.\n\n==Family==\nTaylor in 1805 married Ann Pring, sister to [[Daniel Pring]]. They began a family at Holwell House, [[Whitchurch, Devon]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=W. H. Brock|author2=A. J. Meadows|title=The Lamp of Learning: Taylor & Francis And Two Centuries Of Publishing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J74foasxvOAC&pg=PA33|accessdate=12 April 2013|date=1 April 1998|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-203-21167-0|page=33}}</ref><ref>Philip Meadows Taylor, ''A Memoir of the family of Taylor of Norwich'' (1886), p. 16;[http://wayward.archive.org/stream/memoiroffamilyof00tayl#page/n39/mode/2up archive.org.]</ref>\n\nIn 1829, Taylor and his family played host to composer [[Felix Mendelssohn]] at their country home in Wales.  While there, Mendelssohn composed several works, including his operetta [[Die Heimkehr aus der Fremde|Son and Stranger]] for his parents' silver wedding anniversary, an organ work for his sister's wedding, and three piano fantasias written as gifts for Taylor's daughters.<ref name=BBC>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/northeast/sites/flintshire/pages/mendelssohn.shtml Davies, Rhian, \"Mendelssohn in Mold\", BBC Northeast Wales site, accessed November 23, 2009]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|wstitle=Taylor, Philip}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n* {{wikisource author-inline}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taylor, John (Civil Engineer)}}\n[[Category:1779 births]]\n[[Category:1863 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Norwich]]\n[[Category:Mining in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:British civil engineers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Smeatonian Society of Civil Engineers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Geological Society of London]]\n[[Category:British mining engineers]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n[[File:John Taylor (civil engineer).jpg|thumb|250px|John Taylor]]\n'''John Taylor''' (22 August 1779, in [[Norwich]] \u2013 5 April 1863, in London) was a British [[mining engineer]].<ref name=DNB/>\n\n==Life==\nTaylor was the son of [[John Taylor (Unitarian hymn writer)|John]] and [[Susannah Taylor]]. He was the brother of [[Philip Taylor (civil engineer)|Philip Taylor]].<ref name=DNB>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Taylor, Philip}}</ref>\n\n===Business interests===\nMany of Taylor\u2019s business interests were backed by the [[Martineau family]]. In 1796 he improvised a mechanised copper ore crusher at [[Wheal Friendship]], a mine just outside [[Tavistock, Devon]]. This machine was improved over time and became widely adopted; it was known as the \"Cornish rolls\".<ref>{{Cite book\n|last=Earl\n|first=Bryan\n|title=Cornish Mining: The Techniques of Metal Mining in the West of England, Past and Present\n|publisher=Cornish Hillside Publications\n|location=St Austell\n|edition=2nd\n|year=1994\n|page=80\n|isbn=978-0-9519419-3-5}}</ref> Two years later, in 1798, when he was only 19 years old, he became the manager of this mine.<ref name=DNB/><ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/insideout/southwest/series9/week_five.shtml\n|title=BBC Inside Out \u2013 Tavistock Canal\n|publisher=BBC\n|accessdate=10 August 2009}}</ref> Taylor\u2019s sons and [[Peter Finch Martineau]]\u2019s son and grandson were still active in its operations and oversight nearly a century later.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ronalds|first=B.F.|date=February 2018|title=Peter Finch Martineau and his Son|url=|journal=The Martineau Society Newsletter|volume=41|pages=10\u201319|via=}}</ref> \n\nFrom 1803 to 1817 Taylor oversaw the construction of the [[Tavistock Canal]], which linked the town of Tavistock to [[Morwellham Quay]] on the [[River Tamar]], where cargo was loaded into ships.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.towpathtreks.co.uk/Other/tavistock_canal.html\n|title=Towpath Treks: The Tavistock Canal and Morwellham Quay\n|publisher=towpathtreks.co.uk\n|accessdate=10 August 2009}}</ref><ref name=CORN>\n{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.cornish-mining.org.uk/pdf/Cornwall_west_devon_Mining_Landscape_WHS_Nomination_Document_Parts3b_c_d_e.pdf\n |title       = The Cornwall and West Devon Mining Landscape Description of Property, 3b\n |publisher   = Cornwall Council\n |accessdate  = 10 August 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071004233515/http://www.cornish-mining.org.uk/pdf/Cornwall_west_devon_Mining_Landscape_WHS_Nomination_Document_Parts3b_c_d_e.pdf\n |archivedate = 4 October 2007\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1812 Taylor set up as a chemical manufacturer at [[Stratford, Essex]].<ref name=DNB/> This enterprise, also funded by the Martineaus, set out to produce [[vitriol]], but as Taylor & Martineau became widely diversified.<ref name=\"ODNB\">{{cite ODNB|id=27059|title=Taylor, John|first=Edmund|last=Newell}}</ref> One of Taylor's interests was sugar refining, for which he took out a patent in 1815 for a pressure method for separation of sugar from [[molasses]]. The use of heated animal oils in sugar processes disclosed the production of [[naphtha]].<ref>[[June Z. Fullmer]], ''Technology, Chemistry, and the Law in Early 19th-Century England'', Technology and Culture Vol. 21, No. 1 (Jan. 1980), pp. 1\u201328, at p. 8 and p. 16. Published by: The Johns Hopkins University Press on behalf of the Society for the History of Technology. Stable URL: https://www.jstor.org/stable/3103985</ref> Taylor took out another patent in 1815, for decomposing animal oils into gas.<ref>{{cite book|author=William Matthews|title=An historical sketch of the origin and progress of gas-lighting|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PZpLAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA95|accessdate=12 April 2013|year=1832|publisher=Simpkin & Marshall|page=95}}</ref> This discovery led Taylor & Martineau into 1823 to what Philip Taylor's son later wrote of as \"the battle of the gases\": the commercial contest between [[gas lighting]] derived from coal and from oils.<ref>Philip Meadows Taylor, ''A Memoir of the family of Taylor of Norwich'' (1886), p. 52;[http://wayward.archive.org/stream/memoiroffamilyof00tayl#page/n111/mode/2up archive.org.]</ref> John Taylor's direction in the 1820s, however, was back into mining.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n\nIn 1819 Taylor raised the \u00a365,000 needed to re-open the [[Consolidated Mines]] in [[Gwennap]], Cornwall. This mine employed over 3,000 people and became the most productive in Cornwall, yielding almost 450,000 tons of copper ore.<ref>{{Cite book\n|last=Barton\n|first=D. B.\n|title=A History of Copper Mining in Cornwall and Devon\n|publisher=D. Bradford Barton Ltd\n|location=Truro\n|year=1978\n|edition=3rd\n|pages=51, 95\n|isbn=}}</ref> He was also mineral agent to the [[Duke of Devonshire]] and to the commissioners of [[Greenwich Hospital (London)|Greenwich Hospital]].<ref name=DNB/>\n\nIn 1824 he built the [[Redruth and Chasewater Railway]] to transport the ore from Consolidated Mines and others nearby to the port at [[Devoran]].<ref name=CORN/>\n\nIn 1824 he also began a major expansion of the copper mines at [[Coniston, Cumbria|Coniston]] in [[Cumbria]], making them \"the largest and most profitable copper mines in the north\".<ref name=\"Cumbria-industries-copper-mining\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cumbria-industries.org.uk/a-z-of-industries/copper/ |title=Copper |last=Fleming |first=P. |date=2014 |website=Industrial History of Cumbria |access-date=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1836 he erected a new engine at [[Penrhyn D\u00fb Mines|Penrhyn Du]] and held a lease from 1838<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bennett|first=John|title=Metal Mines Of Llanengan|last2=Vernon|first2=Robert|publisher=Gwydyr Mines Publications|year=|isbn=0951479881|location=Cheshire|pages=40}}</ref>\n\n===Intellectual life===\nIn 1807 Taylor was elected a Fellow of the [[Geological Society]], and acted as treasurer from 1816 to 1844. In 1825 he was elected a Fellow of the [[Royal Society]], and was one of the founders of the [[British Association]] on 26 June 1832, holding the office of treasurer till September 1861. He was one of the founders of [[University College, London]], to which he acted as treasurer for many years.<ref name=DNB/>\n\n==Works==\nTaylor was the author of ''Statements concerning the Profits of Mining in England'' (London, 1825), edited ''Records of Mining'' in 1829, and contributed articles to scientific journals.<ref name=DNB/> A list of his publications may be found in the appendix of R. Burt, ''John Taylor, mining entrepreneur and engineer, 1779\u20131863'', Moorland Publishing Company, 1977. He contributed articles on mining to ''[[Rees's Cyclop\u00e6dia]]''.\n\n==Family==\nTaylor in 1805 married Ann Pring, sister to [[Daniel Pring]]. They began a family at Holwell House, [[Whitchurch, Devon]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=W. H. Brock|author2=A. J. Meadows|title=The Lamp of Learning: Taylor & Francis And Two Centuries Of Publishing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J74foasxvOAC&pg=PA33|accessdate=12 April 2013|date=1 April 1998|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-203-21167-0|page=33}}</ref><ref>Philip Meadows Taylor, ''A Memoir of the family of Taylor of Norwich'' (1886), p. 16;[http://wayward.archive.org/stream/memoiroffamilyof00tayl#page/n39/mode/2up archive.org.]</ref>\n\nIn 1829, Taylor and his family played host to composer [[Felix Mendelssohn]] at their country home in Wales.  While there, Mendelssohn composed several works, including his operetta [[Die Heimkehr aus der Fremde|Son and Stranger]] for his parents' silver wedding anniversary, an organ work for his sister's wedding, and three piano fantasias written as gifts for Taylor's daughters.<ref name=BBC>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/northeast/sites/flintshire/pages/mendelssohn.shtml Davies, Rhian, \"Mendelssohn in Mold\", BBC Northeast Wales site, accessed November 23, 2009]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|wstitle=Taylor, Philip}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{wikisource author-inline}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taylor, John (Civil Engineer)}}\n[[Category:1779 births]]\n[[Category:1863 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Norwich]]\n[[Category:Mining in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:British civil engineers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Smeatonian Society of Civil Engineers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Geological Society of London]]\n[[Category:British mining engineers]]\n", "name_user": "Gazamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:AddedPortal:Cornwall", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Taylor_(mining_engineer)"}
