q_mi         =\n|area_land_sq_mi          =\n|area_water_sq_mi         =\n|area_water_percent       =\n|area_urban_km2           =\n|area_urban_sq_mi         =\n|area_metro_km2           =\n|area_metro_sq_mi         =\n|area_blank1_title        =\n|area_blank1_km2          =\n|area_blank1_sq_mi        =\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2015\n|pop_est_footnotes      =<ref>{{cite report |url=http://proyectos.inei.gob.pe/web/biblioineipub/bancopub/Est/Lib1020/cuadros/c0206.xls |title=Per\u00fa: Poblaci\u00f3n estimada al 30 de junio y tasa de crecimiento de las ciudades capitales, por departamento, 2011 y 2015 |work=Per\u00fa: Estimaciones y proyecciones de poblaci\u00f3n total por sexo de las principales ciudades, 2012-2015 |publisher=Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica e Inform\u00e1tica |date=March 2012 |access-date=2015-06-03}}</ref>\n|population_est         =371012\n|population_as_of                = \n|population_footnotes            =\n|population_note                 =\n|population_total                = \n|population_density_km2          = 3019\n|population_density_sq_mi        =\n|population_metro                =\n|population_density_metro_km2    =\n|population_density_metro_sq_mi  =\n|population_urban                =\n|population_density_urban_km2    =\n|population_density_urban_sq_mi  =\n|population_blank1_title         =\n|population_blank1               =\n|population_density_blank1_km2   =\n|population_density_blank1_sq_mi =\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone               = [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]-5\n|utc_offset             =\n|timezone_DST           =\n|utc_offset_DST         =\n|coordinates              = {{coord|9|8|28.36|S|78|35|36.86|W|region:PE|display=inline}}\n|elevation_footnotes    =  <!--for references: use<ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            = 4\n|elevation_ft           =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & related -->\n|postal_code_type       =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code            =\n|area_code              = 43\n|blank_name             = \n|blank_info             = \n|blank1_name            =\n|blank1_info            =\n|website                = [http://www.munisanta.gob.pe/ www.munisanta.gob.pe]\n|footnotes              =\n}}\n'''Chimbote'''  {{IPA-es|t\u0283im\u02c8bote||Es - Chimbote.ogg}}; [[Quechuan languages|Quechua]]: Chimputi) is the largest city in the [[Ancash Region]] of [[Peru]], and the capital of both [[Santa Province]] and [[Chimbote District]].\n\nThe city is located on the coast in [[Ferrol Bay]], 130 [[km]] south of [[Trujillo, Peru|Trujillo]] and {{convert|420|km|mi|sp=us}} north of [[Lima, Peru|Lima]] on the [[Pan-American Highway (South America)|North Pan-American highway]]. It is the start of a chain of important cities on the [[Peru]]vian north coast like [[Trujillo, Peru|Trujillo]], [[Chiclayo]] and [[Piura]]. The advantages of this geographic location made Chimbote into a transshipment junction for the [[Santa River]] [[valley]].\n\n==History==\nIn 1835, when General [[Andr\u00e9s de Santa Cruz|Santa Cruz]] granted Chimbote's first official acknowledgement, Chimbote was a village of [[fishermen]] with a population of no more than 800.\n\nIn 1871, an agreement was made with [[Henry Meiggs]] to build a [[railroad]] towards the interior of the country. Chimbote was classified as a [[port]], even though its population remained around 1,000. The opening of the [[Pan-American Highway (South America)|Pan-American Highway]] created easy access to Lima in the 1930s. In 1881, there was an attempt to cede a naval base to the U.S. in Chimbote Bay by Peru. The deal was blocked by Chile who sent its marines to occupy Chimbote after learning of the deal to cede a naval base to the U.S. Navy.\n\nIn 1940, Chimbote was still a small [[fishing port]], with only 2,400 inhabitants in an urbanized area of {{convert|80|ha|km2 sqmi|sp=us|abbr=out}}. In 1943, the government created the [[Corporaci\u00f3n Peruana del Santa]] (Peruvian Corporation of Santa). This entity assumed ownership of the [[railroad]], made improvements to the [[port]], and began work on a [[hydroelectric power station]] on the R\u00edo Santa (in the [[Ca\u00f1\u00f3n del Pato]] <nowiki>[Duck Canyon]</nowiki> in [[Huallanca District, Bolognesi|Huallanca]]). The first stage of the power station was inaugurated in 1958; also that year, an iron and steel plant was built.<ref group=\"nb\">The iron and steel plant is currently{{When|date=September 2010}} known as Empresa Sider\u00fargica del Per\u00fa S.A.A.</ref> By 1943, the first companies dedicated to the extraction of liver from the [[Sarda chiliensis|Pacific bonito]] fish arrived. This liver was sold for a high price abroad due to World&nbsp;War&nbsp;II.\n\n== Geography ==\n\n=== Climate ===\nChimbote's climate is comfortable, despite being located in the tropics and in a desert. Although classified as subtropical, Chimbote's proximity to the cool [[Humboldt current]] leads to temperatures much cooler than those expected for a tropical desert, and is classified as a [[desert climate]]. On average, the warmest month is February with temperatures a little over {{convert|26|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|0}}. September is considered the average coolest month, at around {{convert|13|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|0}}. The annual average temperature is around 20 \u00b0C (68 \u00b0F).\n\nThe city gets little to no precipitation; however, thick fog predominates through the months of May to November, usually overnight. Rainfall usually comes in February.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Chimbote (1961\u20131990)\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan high C = 26.7\n|Feb high C = 27.8\n|Mar high C = 27.4\n|Apr high C = 25.5\n|May high C = 23.9\n|Jun high C = 22.8\n|Jul high C = 21.9\n|Aug high C = 21.5\n|Sep high C = 21.5\n|Oct high C = 22.4\n|Nov high C = 23.8\n|Dec high C = 25.3\n|year high C = 24.2\n|Jan low C = 17.4\n|Feb low C = 18.3\n|Mar low C = 18.3\n|Apr low C = 17.0\n|May low C = 15.7\n|Jun low C = 14.6\n|Jul low C = 13.9\n|Aug low C = 14.0\n|Sep low C = 13.7\n|Oct low C = 14.2\n|Nov low C = 14.8\n|Dec low C = 16.2\n|year low C = 15.7\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 1.6\n|Feb precipitation mm = 3.7\n|Mar precipitation mm = 3.6\n|Apr precipitation mm = 1.6\n|May precipitation mm = 0.2\n|Jun precipitation mm = 0.0\n|Jul precipitation mm = 0.3\n|Aug precipitation mm = 0.2\n|Sep precipitation mm = 0.0\n|Oct precipitation mm = 0.2\n|Nov precipitation mm = 0.2\n|Dec precipitation mm = 0.3\n|year precipitation mm = 11.9\n|source 1 = NOAA<ref name = NOAA>\n{{cite web\n| url = ftp://ftp.atdd.noaa.gov/pub/GCOS/WMO-Normals/TABLES/REGIII/PR/84531.TXT\n| title = Chimbote Climate Normals 1961\u20131990\n| publisher = [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]\n| accessdate = April 23, 2015}}</ref>\n|date=April 2015\n}}\n\n==Population==\n[[Image:Satellite photo of Chimbote Peru.jpg|thumb|180px|right|Satellite image of Chimbote]]\nA large number of people migrated to Chimbote in the early 1970s. By that time, less than 5 percent of the people from Chimbote would truly consider themselves native; between 1960 and 1970, Chimbote's population multiplied by more than a hundred times. In 1900, the population of the port was 1,400; after 1970, it was 170,000. As of 2005, its population was 324,398.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.citypopulation.de/Peru-Chimbote.html|title=Peru - Chimbote Agglomeration|work=www.citypopulation.de|last=Brinkhoff|first=Thomas|date=20 April 2007|accessdate=6 September 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080702015740/http://www.citypopulation.de/Peru-Chimbote.html|archive-date=2 July 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe influx of residents was closely bound to the creation of the Corporaci\u00f3n Peruana del Santa, to the start and development of the [[fishing]] industry, and to the establishment of the iron and steel plant (\"[[SIDERPERU|Siderperu]]\"). Together, these multiplied the commercial and productive activities of the port. At the beginning of 1996, as [[Peru]]vian public companies were privatized,  the Peruvian-Brazilian company Acerco bought Siderperu.\n\n===Districts and neighborhoods===\nThe city of Chimbote, being a district itself, comprises 7 more districts: Santa, Coishco, Samanco, Nepe\u00f1a, Macate, Moro, C\u00e1ceres del Per\u00fa, and Nuevo Chimbote. The neighborhoods of El Barrio de Acero, Barrio Bolivar, El Progreso, Miraflores Alto and Miraflores Bajo surround Chimbote.\n\n==Economy==\n\nDuring the 1970s, the [[El Ni\u00f1o]] climate pattern, an [[earthquake]], and overfishing drastically affected the fishing industry, and restrictions were imposed to ensure its survival. More than 75 percent of Peru's fishing industry is based in Chimbote.\n\nChimbote is the largest fishing port in the world.<ref>https://www.pewtrusts.org/en/research-and-analysis/articles/2016/01/05/new-analysis-identifies-worlds-largest-and-busiest-fishing-ports</ref> Chimbote has more than 30 fish factories. Chimbote's active [[commerce]] and its diversified industrial development are characteristic of the city. Its population includes workers who have experience in [[fishing]], naval, [[canning]], and the iron-and-steel industry with the company [[SIDERPERU]].\n\nChimbote also has beaches that support tourism.\n\n===Peruvian anchoveta \"boom\"===\n\nShortly after the fish [[canning industry]] declined, the industrialization of [[Peruvian anchoveta|anchoveta]] fishing peaked. This attracted people from all over Peru, due to the high wages paid in the fishing industry at the time, fueling Chimbote's suburban growth. The strong migratory wave toward the city increased because of the serious crisis of the countryside in the 1960s, particularly in [[Ancash]], [[Cajamarca]] and the northern part of [[La Libertad Region]]. The axis of development moved from the [[Gossypium barbadense|Pima cotton]], [[sugarcane]], and [[rice]] plantations to the large city. In addition, Chimbote was a natural exit [[Channel (geography)|channel]] for the exports of the [[Santa Province|Santa valley]], and a starting point for the entry to the [[Callej\u00f3n de Huaylas]].\n\nThe Peruvian anchoveta [[Boom and bust|boom]] created wealth in the city, but it soon ended due to indiscriminate [[fishing]] that overwhelmed the [[bio-mass]]. An [[earthquake]] in 1970 damaged to the facilities of the [[Fishing industry|fishing industries]], causing [[unemployment]] and [[Poverty|impoverishment]]. During this period, the [[Diocese of Chimbote]] created the Social Welfare Commission, to organize diverse popular dining places in conjunction with [[UNICEF]].{{Vague|date=September 2010}} Since the 1960s, the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Pittsburgh]] has served the poor at the Chimbote Mission, raising funds through the Chimbote Foundation.<ref name=\"Chimbote Foundation\">{{cite news|url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/valleyindependent/news/s_192679.html|title=Local school children provide help for counterparts in Peru|last=Lelik|first=Emma Jene|date=5 May 2004|work=The Valley Independent|publisher=The Tribune-Review Publishing Company|page=1|accessdate=17 Dec 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090502013106/http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/valleyindependent/news/s_192679.html|archive-date=2 May 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Tourism==\n\nChimbote is surrounded by two natural bays, the Bay of Chimbote (or Ferrol) and the Bay of Samanco, both with excellent [[harbor]] conditions. Chimbote forms a [[conurbation]] with [[Nuevo Chimbote District]] to the south. Between these districts, the Humedales de Villa Mar\u00eda, a [[swamp]], is home to a local species of [[heron]], along with many species of [[frog]]s and fish. The swamp is formed by the [[Lacramarca River]].\n\nTo the south of the city, there are many beaches, such as [[Besique|Vesique]], [[Los Chim\u00fas (beach)|Los Chim\u00fas]], [[Tortugas beach|Tortugas]], [[Caleta Colorada]] and [[El Dorado beach|el Dorado]]. Also located near Chimbote is the [[Blanca Island|Isla Blanca]] (''white isle'', in English), which takes its name from the white color of the ground. Isla Blanca measures approximately {{convert|3200|m|ft|sp=us}} in length and {{convert|920|m|ft|sp=us}} in width, and reaches {{convert|204|m|ft|sp=us}} above sea level.\n\nLocated next to the city is the Cerro de la Juventud (Mountain of Youth), also called Cerro de la Paz (Mountain of Peace). Since 1985, this tourist attraction attracts hundreds annually. Visitors appreciate a panoramic view of Chimbote's bay from the top of this mountain. Tourists can also visit Isla Blanca Boulevard, which has many beautiful marble sculptures and fountains.\n\n[[File:Cruz Por La Paz - Cross at the top of Cerro de la Juventud aka Cerro de la Paz.jpg|thumb|Cross at the top of Cerro de la Juventud (Mountain of Youth) aka Cerro de la Paz (Mountain of Peace)]]\n\nFrom Chimbote, some short tourist circuits can be taken:\n* Chimbote - [[Casma]] - Sech\u00edn - Yaut\u00e1n\n* Chimbote - [[Nepe\u00f1a District|Nepe\u00f1a]] - [[San Jacinto (Peru)|San Jacinto]] - [[Moro (Peru)|Moro]] -[[Jimbe (Peru)|Jimbe]]\n* Chimbote - [[Santa Province|Santa]] - [[Huallanca District, Huaylas|Huallanca]]\n\nThe city is known for its ''[[ceviche]]'', a popular Peruvian dish whose ingredients include [[whitefish (fisheries term)|white fish]], [[octopus]], [[seashell]], [[squid]], [[crab]], and [[Capsicum annuum|red hot pepper]].\n\n[[File:Panoramica chimbote desde Cerro de la Paz.jpg|640px|thumb|center|View of the city of Chimbote from the Cerro de la Paz.]]\n\n==Festivals==\nChimbote has two important celebrations during the year: Holy Week and The Festivity of ''San Pedrito of Chimbote'' (also called ''Chimbote's Civic Anniversary'').\n*'''[[Festival of San Pedrito of Chimbote|Patronal feast of San Pedrito]]''', this festival has its origins in the 16th century with the first fishermen who populated Chimbote coming from [[Huanchaco]]. It is held from 23 to 30 June in devotion to the patron saint of fishermen San Pedro. The central feast day is on 29 June, the image of the saint is taken out in procession and It is paraded through the bay by boat.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.munisanta.gob.pe/web/institucional/nuestraciudad/nuestraciudad.php|title =Fiesta de San Pedrito|accessdate =3 September 2013|url-status =dead|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20140510134350/http://www.munisanta.gob.pe/web/institucional/nuestraciudad/nuestraciudad.php|archivedate =10 May 2014|df =dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nThe [[Academia Preuniversitaria \"Perpetuo Socorro\"]] and the [[Catholic University Los Angeles of Chimbote]] are located in Chimbote.\n\n==Transportation==\n\nThe Chimbote-[[Huallanca District, Huaylas|Huallanca]] rail line, built in 1922, serves as a [[railway]] for [[coal]] and [[iron]] mines on the interior and a railway for the river valley by transporting [[rice]], [[cotton]], [[sugarcane]], and [[banana]]s.\n\n===Bus terminal===\n\nEl Chimbador Bus Terminal is Chimbote's primary ground transportation facility. The bus terminal is located outside of the city. It has become a vital connection for the region's workers, travelers and visitors, serving nearly 6,000 passengers a day.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}} Currently{{When|date=September 2010}} there are 30 bus carriers offering services for national and international travel.\n\n===Port===\nThe port of Chimbote is considered by some one of the most beautiful and safest ports in the [[Chala|Peruvian coast]]. It extends {{convert|12|km|mi|sp=us}}, from [[Caleta Colorada]] Bay (Red Creek Bay) in the north, where the present marine facilities are located, to [[Anconcillo]] in the south.\n\n===Airport===\nThe city is served by the [[Tnte. FAP Jaime Montreuil Morales Airport|Teniente FAP Jaime Montreuil Morales Airport]], operated by CORPAC S.A. It was created in 1957 under the government of President [[Manuel Prado Ugarteche]]. There are regular flights to Lima by [[LC Busre]].\n\n==Sister cities==\n* {{Flagicon|Paraguay}} [[Asunci\u00f3n]], [[Paraguay]]\n* {{Flagicon|Argentina}} [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]]\n* {{Flagicon|Brazil}} [[Belo Horizonte]], [[Brazil]]\n* {{Flagicon|Peru}} [[Huancayo]], [[Peru]]\n* {{Flagicon|Japan}} [[Yokohama]], [[Japan]]\n* {{Flagicon|France}} [[Nantes]], [[France]]\n* {{Flagicon|Spain}} [[Madrid]], [[Spain]]\n* {{Flagicon|United States}} [[Pensacola, Florida|Pensacola]], [[United States]]\n* {{Flagicon|Costa Rica}} [[San Jos\u00e9]], [[Costa Rica]]\n* {{Flagicon|United States}} [[Seattle]], [[United States]]\n* {{Flagicon|United States}} [[Pittsburgh]], [[United States]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Peru}}\n*[[Ancash Region]]\n*[[1970 Ancash earthquake]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Chimbote}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Large cities of Peru}}\n{{Coord|9|4|28.36|S|78|35|36.86|W|region:PE_type:city|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Populated places in the Ancash Region]]\n[[Category:Port cities in Peru]]\n[[Category:Cities in Peru]]\n<ref>https://chimbotefoundation.org/</ref>\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:San Jos\u00e9\u2192San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chimbote"}
{"title_page": "William Husband", "text_new": "{{For|the Scottish association footballer|William Husband (footballer)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox engineer\n|image                = \n|image_width          =\n|caption              =\n|name                 = William Husband\n|nationality          = British\n|birth_date           = 13 October 1822\n|birth_place          = [[Mylor, Cornwall]]\n|death_date           = {{Death date and age|1887|4|10|1822|10|13|df=y}}\n|death_place          = [[Clifton, Bristol]]\n|education            =\n|spouse               = Anne Nanney\n|parents              = James Husband\n|children             = Four\n|discipline           = [[Civil engineering|Civil]] and [[mechanical engineer]]\n|institutions         =\n|practice_name        =\n|significant_projects = drainage of [[Haarlemmermeer|Haarlem Lake]], Netherlands\n|significant_design   =\n|significant_advance  =\n|significant_awards   =\n}}\n\n'''William Husband''' (13 October 1822 \u2013 10 April 1887) was a British [[civil engineer|civil]] and [[mechanical engineer]] of the 19th century.\n\n==Biography==\nHusband, born at [[Mylor, Cornwall]], on 13 October 1822, was eldest son of James Husband, shipbuilder and surveyor for [[Lloyd's Register]] at [[Falmouth, Cornwall|Falmouth]], who died in 1859. He was educated first by Edgcombe Rimell, curate of [[Mabe, Cornwall|Mabe]], and afterwards at Bellevue Academy, [[Penryn, Cornwall|Penryn]].<ref name=\"dnb\">{{cite web | last =Boase | first =G. C.| authorlink = George Clement Boase|title =Husband, William (1822\u20131887), civil and mechanical engineer  | work = [[Dictionary of National Biography]] Vol. XXIIX | publisher =Smith, Elder & Co.  | year = 1891 | url = http://www.oxforddnb.com/templates/olddnb.jsp?articleid=14258 | accessdate = 21 December 2007}} {{DNBfirst|wstitle=Husband, William}}</ref>\n\n===Haarlem Lake===\nHusband declined to be either a sailor or a shipbuilder, as his father desired, and instead was in 1839 apprenticed for four years to [[Harvey & Co]], engineers and ironfounders, of [[Hayle]], Cornwall. His steadiness and ability soon won for him the esteem of his employers, and in 1843, when they had built the Leigh water engine for the drainage of [[Haarlemmermeer|Haarlem Lake]], he was sent to the [[Netherlands]] to superintend its erection. As the machinery could not be landed for some time on account of the ice, he went to the village school at Sassenheym to learn [[Dutch language|Dutch]]. In six months he wrote and spoke it with fluency. On the death of the mechanical engineer in charge of the steam machinery on the drainage works in 1845, he succeeded to that post, when he planned and erected the half-weg engine. The lake when drained added {{convert|47000|acre|km2}} of rich [[Alluvium|alluvial]] soil to the country, and being situated in the midst of populous provinces proved of material importance. [[William II of the Netherlands|King William]] expressed his satisfaction, and on 13 March 1848 Husband was elected a member of the Koninklijk Instituut van Ingenieurs. In 1849 he suffered so severely from ague, from the effects of which he never fully recovered, that he resigned his situation and returned to England.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\n===Other works===\nWhile in the Netherlands, in conjunction with his friends Colonel Wiebeking and Professor Munnich, he invented a plan for drying and warehousing grain at a small cost, and preserving it in good condition for years. On 2 May 1851 he submitted to [[Sir George Grey, 2nd Baronet|Sir George Grey]] a plan for a powder magazine in the [[River Mersey|Mersey]], on the recommendation of the [[Liverpool City Council|Liverpool town council]]. At the invitation of T. E. Blackwell, C.E., he went to [[Clifton, Bristol|Clifton]] to assist in some works in the [[Port of Bristol|Bristol docks]], when he planned a bridge for the [[Cumberland Basin (Bristol)|Cumberland basin]]. In September 1852 he undertook the management of the London business of the firm of Harvey & Company; in June 1854 he returned to Hayle to take the charge of the engineering department, and in 1863 became managing partner. He resumed the management of the business in London in October 1885, where he remained until his death.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\nIn practical knowledge of [[Hydraulic machinery|hydraulic]] and mining machinery Husband was surpassed by few. In June 1859 he submitted to the [[admiralty]] a plan for a floating [[Artillery battery|battery]], and patented the following inventions: the balance valve for water-work purposes (this superseded the costly stand-pipe), the four-beat pump-valve, a safety plug for the prevention of boiler explosions, and a safety equilibrium cataract, used with the Cornish pumping engine for the prevention of accidents. He also effected many improvements in pneumatic ore stamps, finally perfecting and patenting those now known as Husband's oscillating cylinder stamps.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\nDuring the last two years of his life he was employed in carrying out contracts for the pumping machinery at the [[Severn Tunnel]], and at the time of his death was planning further improvements in Cornish pumping engines.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\n===Professional and other interests===\nOn 1 May 1866 he was elected a member of the [[Institution of Civil Engineers]], and during 1881 and 1882 served as president of the [[Miners Association]] and [[Royal Institution of Cornwall]]. He actively supported the [[Royal Cornwall Polytechnic Society]]. In 1855 he planned and superintended the erection of a breakwater at [[Porthleven]] in [[Mount's Bay]], thereby making it a safe harbour. He helped to secure a water supply for Hayle and a system of drainage. He originated and became first captain of the 8th Cornwall artillery volunteers in April 1860, a post which he held till 1865. He established science classes at Hayle in connection with South Kensington. In [[Spectroscopy|spectrum analysis]] and astronomy he took a great interest, and made many observations with a {{convert|10.25|in|mm|adj=on}} telescope. On 28 and 29 March 1887, in company with Sir [[John Hawkshaw]] and Mr. Hayter, C.E., he was employed in inspecting nine pumping engines which his firm had erected in the Severn tunnel for keeping down the water.\n\n===Marriage and death===\nOn 20 June 1850 he married Anne, fifth daughter of Edward Nanney, by whom he had a family of four children. He died on 10 April 1887 of an attack of gall stones at his lodgings, 26 Sion Hill, Clifton, Bristol, and was buried at [[St. Erth]], Cornwall, 16 April. In 1890 a sum of \u00a3800. was raised to establish a Husband scholarship for the technical education of miners.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{DNB|wstitle=Husband, William}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Husband, William}}\n[[Category:1822 births]]\n[[Category:1887 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Mylor, Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Mining in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Cornish engineers]]\n[[Category:British civil engineers]]\n[[Category:Haarlemmermeer]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the Scottish association footballer|William Husband (footballer)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox engineer\n|image                = \n|image_width          =\n|caption              =\n|name                 = William Husband\n|nationality          = British\n|birth_date           = 13 October 1822\n|birth_place          = [[Mylor, Cornwall]]\n|death_date           = {{Death date and age|1887|4|10|1822|10|13|df=y}}\n|death_place          = [[Clifton, Bristol]]\n|education            =\n|spouse               = Anne Nanney\n|parents              = James Husband\n|children             = Four\n|discipline           = [[Civil engineering|Civil]] and [[mechanical engineer]]\n|institutions         =\n|practice_name        =\n|significant_projects = drainage of [[Haarlemmermeer|Haarlem Lake]], Netherlands\n|significant_design   =\n|significant_advance  =\n|significant_awards   =\n}}\n\n'''William Husband''' (13 October 1822 \u2013 10 April 1887) was a British [[civil engineer|civil]] and [[mechanical engineer]] of the 19th century.\n\n==Biography==\nHusband, born at [[Mylor, Cornwall]], on 13 October 1822, was eldest son of James Husband, shipbuilder and surveyor for [[Lloyd's Register]] at [[Falmouth, Cornwall|Falmouth]], who died in 1859. He was educated first by Edgcombe Rimell, curate of [[Mabe, Cornwall|Mabe]], and afterwards at Bellevue Academy, [[Penryn, Cornwall|Penryn]].<ref name=\"dnb\">{{cite web | last =Boase | first =G. C.| authorlink = George Clement Boase|title =Husband, William (1822\u20131887), civil and mechanical engineer  | work = [[Dictionary of National Biography]] Vol. XXIIX | publisher =Smith, Elder & Co.  | year = 1891 | url = http://www.oxforddnb.com/templates/olddnb.jsp?articleid=14258 | accessdate = 21 December 2007}} {{DNBfirst|wstitle=Husband, William}}</ref>\n\n===Haarlem Lake===\nHusband declined to be either a sailor or a shipbuilder, as his father desired, and instead was in 1839 apprenticed for four years to [[Harvey & Co]], engineers and ironfounders, of [[Hayle]], Cornwall. His steadiness and ability soon won for him the esteem of his employers, and in 1843, when they had built the Leigh water engine for the drainage of [[Haarlemmermeer|Haarlem Lake]], he was sent to the [[Netherlands]] to superintend its erection. As the machinery could not be landed for some time on account of the ice, he went to the village school at Sassenheym to learn [[Dutch language|Dutch]]. In six months he wrote and spoke it with fluency. On the death of the mechanical engineer in charge of the steam machinery on the drainage works in 1845, he succeeded to that post, when he planned and erected the half-weg engine. The lake when drained added {{convert|47000|acre|km2}} of rich [[Alluvium|alluvial]] soil to the country, and being situated in the midst of populous provinces proved of material importance. [[William II of the Netherlands|King William]] expressed his satisfaction, and on 13 March 1848 Husband was elected a member of the Koninklijk Instituut van Ingenieurs. In 1849 he suffered so severely from ague, from the effects of which he never fully recovered, that he resigned his situation and returned to England.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\n===Other works===\nWhile in the Netherlands, in conjunction with his friends Colonel Wiebeking and Professor Munnich, he invented a plan for drying and warehousing grain at a small cost, and preserving it in good condition for years. On 2 May 1851 he submitted to [[Sir George Grey, 2nd Baronet|Sir George Grey]] a plan for a powder magazine in the [[River Mersey|Mersey]], on the recommendation of the [[Liverpool City Council|Liverpool town council]]. At the invitation of T. E. Blackwell, C.E., he went to [[Clifton, Bristol|Clifton]] to assist in some works in the [[Port of Bristol|Bristol docks]], when he planned a bridge for the [[Cumberland Basin (Bristol)|Cumberland basin]]. In September 1852 he undertook the management of the London business of the firm of Harvey & Company; in June 1854 he returned to Hayle to take the charge of the engineering department, and in 1863 became managing partner. He resumed the management of the business in London in October 1885, where he remained until his death.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\nIn practical knowledge of [[Hydraulic machinery|hydraulic]] and mining machinery Husband was surpassed by few. In June 1859 he submitted to the [[admiralty]] a plan for a floating [[Artillery battery|battery]], and patented the following inventions: the balance valve for water-work purposes (this superseded the costly stand-pipe), the four-beat pump-valve, a safety plug for the prevention of boiler explosions, and a safety equilibrium cataract, used with the Cornish pumping engine for the prevention of accidents. He also effected many improvements in pneumatic ore stamps, finally perfecting and patenting those now known as Husband's oscillating cylinder stamps.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\nDuring the last two years of his life he was employed in carrying out contracts for the pumping machinery at the [[Severn Tunnel]], and at the time of his death was planning further improvements in Cornish pumping engines.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\n===Professional and other interests===\nOn 1 May 1866 he was elected a member of the [[Institution of Civil Engineers]], and during 1881 and 1882 served as president of the [[Miners Association]] and [[Royal Institution of Cornwall]]. He actively supported the [[Royal Cornwall Polytechnic Society]]. In 1855 he planned and superintended the erection of a breakwater at [[Porthleven]] in [[Mount's Bay]], thereby making it a safe harbour. He helped to secure a water supply for Hayle and a system of drainage. He originated and became first captain of the 8th Cornwall artillery volunteers in April 1860, a post which he held till 1865. He established science classes at Hayle in connection with South Kensington. In [[Spectroscopy|spectrum analysis]] and astronomy he took a great interest, and made many observations with a {{convert|10.25|in|mm|adj=on}} telescope. On 28 and 29 March 1887, in company with Sir [[John Hawkshaw]] and Mr. Hayter, C.E., he was employed in inspecting nine pumping engines which his firm had erected in the Severn tunnel for keeping down the water.\n\n===Marriage and death===\nOn 20 June 1850 he married Anne, fifth daughter of Edward Nanney, by whom he had a family of four children. He died on 10 April 1887 of an attack of gall stones at his lodgings, 26 Sion Hill, Clifton, Bristol, and was buried at [[St. Erth]], Cornwall, 16 April. In 1890 a sum of \u00a3800. was raised to establish a Husband scholarship for the technical education of miners.<ref name=\"dnb\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{DNB|wstitle=Husband, William}}\n\n{{authority c